===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|nl|ijsberg}}, compound of {{m|nl|ijs||ice}} + {{m|nl|berg||mountain}}. First used to describe a glacier as seen at a distance from a ship then used as a term to describe the floating chunks of ice broken off from such glaciers. Compare German {{m|de|Eisberg}}, Danish {{m|da|isbjerg}}, Norwegian/Swedish {{m|no|isberg}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈaɪsbɜːɡ/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈaɪsbɝɡ/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A huge mass of ocean-floating [[ice]] which has broken off a [[glacier]] or [[ice shelf]]
#: {{ux|en|The Titanic hit an '''iceberg''' and sank.}}
# {{lb|en|US|slang}} An [[aloof]] [[person]].
# {{lb|en|figuratively|after an adjective}} An [[impending]] [[disastrous]] [[event]] whose adverse [[effect]]s are only beginning to show, in reference to one-tenth of the [[volume]] of an iceberg being visible above [[water]].
